WRITING.TEXT: Had two experiences, both in SF on the same block where my office was at the time. One guy, let's call him Bob, was usually at a trashcan on the corner a few days a week. Had a cane, very friendly dude. He would always say hi and after a while, I made it a point to bring change for him and wave. Took me a while to work up the courage to talk to him. Turns out he used to be in the IT industry back in the 80s but due to a string of bad luck (including declining health), he ended up on the street. After that (which was a 10 minute conversation and taught me to slow down and ask questions- I'm typically shy when it comes to people on the street) I made a point to buy him coffees, food, even gave him an old Kindle Fire before I moved. We ended up knowing each other by name (more on that in a moment). The second person, let's call her Grandma. She reminded me of my Grandma, so I naturally felt sorry for her when she would show up under a sign every other week or so. Every time I saw her, I bought her a coffee and a danish, without her prompting me. Every time, she gave me this look like I changed her entire world that day. I never got to learn more about her (she was never around long enough- she was always gone when I left work). I hope she was ok- I wish I could have done more for her. So I left SF to work in a different office of the same company. I'm back in town six months later for a conference. Was running to my (former) office with a coworker to pick up some booth supplies and I see Bob. I waved, and he commented "Welcome back! Nice to see you again". My coworker looks at me and exclaims "Wow, even the homeless people know you are back?!" That was kinda cool.

His brother here. I'm absolutely blown away by the outpouring of comments here. He would have been so proud. I remember when his first got that Merc. The second time was to Katie's in his honor (we had a funeral procession of sorts that morning). Don't wait to do something with a loved one.
